 Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Hallon, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hallon, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harding","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Harding</i> (Old English <i>Hearding</i>, literally ‘the hard one’ a derivative of Old English <i>heard</i> ‘hard, harsh, strong, firm, brave’). The surname was first taken to Ireland in the 15th century, and more families of the name settled there 200 years later in Tipperary and surrounding counties.","North German and Dutch: patronymic from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound personal names beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’, or a habitational name from a farm named Harding, of the same etymology.","History: Warren Gamaliel Harding (1865–1923), the 29th president of the US, was born on a farm in OH, of English and Scottish stock on his father's side. Early American bearers of this very common name include Joseph Harding who died at Plymouth in 1633. His great-great grandson Seth was a naval officer during the American Revolution."],"variants":[{"name":"Hardin","meanings":["English: variant of   Harding  .","Altered form of French   Hardouin  .","French: from a pet form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names composed of the element <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Arduino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Francisco, Jose, Luis, Marina, Alberto, Alfonso, Alturo, Angel, Arturo, Azucena, Basilio, Carlos.  Italian Antonio, Gabino.","Italian and Hispanic: from the personal name <i>Arduino</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, akin to   Harding   2."]}]},{"name":"Frances","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Francis .  In the 16th century the two spellings were used indiscriminately for both sexes, the distinction in spelling not being established until the 17th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Frances Harding was born in 1420, in Claverley, Shropshire, England, her father, Richard Harding, was 15 and her mother, Lady Margaret Goulston, was 15. She married Thomas Barker De Calverhall in 1439, in Hallon, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1465, in Hallon, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1420–1465":"1420–1465","1437–1510":"1437–1510","1420–1469":"1420–1469","1436–1464":"1436–1464","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1440–1526":"1440–1526","1462–1531":"1462–1531","1406–1460":"1406–1460","1405–1466":"1405–1466","1440":"1440","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1469":"1469","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","after 1464":"pärast 1464","1439":"1439","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1406":"1406","1516":"1516","1405":"1405","1526":"1526","Claverley, Shropshire, England., United Kingdom":"Claverley, Shropshire, England","Hallon, Shropshire, England":"Hallon, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, England","